SIMPLE: warmth
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Warmth
<hw>Warmth</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The quality
or state of being warm; gentle heat; <as>as, the <ex>warmth</ex> of the
sun; the <ex>warmth</ex> of the blood; vital
<ex>warmth</ex>.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Here kindly <qex>warmth</qex> their mounting juice ferments.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A state of lively and excited interest; zeal; ardor;
fervor; passion; enthusiasm; earnestness; <as>as, the <ex>warmth</ex> of
love or piety; he replied with much <ex>warmth</ex>.</as></def>
⟦ldquo⟧<xex>Spiritual warmth</xex>, and holy fires.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Jer.
Taylor.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That <qex>warmth</qex> . . . which agrees with Christian zeal.</q>
<rj><qau>Sprat.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Paint.)</fld> <def>The glowing effect which arises
from the use of warm colors; hence, any similar appearance or effect in
a painting, or work of color.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Zeal; ardor; fervor; fervency; heat; glow;
earnestness; cordiality; animation; eagerness; excitement;
vehemence.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Warmthless</ent>⟦br⟧
